68—79. All the time you are getting none of the pleasure of your wealth, though you get all its inconvenience.

68. Horace begins as in epic vein, (‘commendandum est hoc pronuntia- tione ³ Acr.,) he is interrupted by a smile from his auditor. Why does he smile? Very possibly, Heindorsanswers (quoting Cic. Tusc. 1. 6. 10 ‘adeone me delirare censes ut ista credam 2 ’) at the reference apparently serious to the old—world myth of Tantalus. Horace hastens to explain that it is an allegory; myth though it be, change only the name and it is strictly true and of yourself.

inhians, keeping even in sleep the look of eager attention.
